WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:03.476
- Thank you, and it's great to be here.

00:00:03.476 --> 00:00:07.579
I was saying earlier
that Rick happens to be

00:00:07.579 --> 00:00:09.504
in the city of Hyderabad.

00:00:09.504 --> 00:00:13.671
Which is the first city in which
I preached my first sermon.

00:00:15.320 --> 00:00:16.992
I was 19 years old at that time.

00:00:16.992 --> 00:00:18.744
It was a youth preacher contest

00:00:18.744 --> 00:00:23.182
and so it happens he's in my
homeland, I'm in his homeland,

00:00:23.182 --> 00:00:26.696
and I was mentioning also that it's

00:00:26.696 --> 00:00:28.908
because I got first choice,

00:00:28.908 --> 00:00:31.520
and I'll explain that to
you, what I mean by that.

00:00:31.520 --> 00:00:34.040
You know, the story is told of an Indian

00:00:34.040 --> 00:00:36.424
who is on a flight and
happened to be sitting

00:00:36.424 --> 00:00:38.360
next to Albert Einstein,

00:00:38.360 --> 00:00:41.852
and so Einstein said Tamil,
this is a long flight.

00:00:41.852 --> 00:00:44.161
Let's play a game as we are flying.

00:00:44.161 --> 00:00:47.104
He said to the Indian
young man next to him,

00:00:47.104 --> 00:00:50.372
I'll ask you a question
and if you can't answer it

00:00:50.372 --> 00:00:51.993
you pay me $50.

00:00:51.993 --> 00:00:54.860
The guy said, this is
ridiculous, you're Einstein.

00:00:54.860 --> 00:00:55.845
He said, no, no, no.

00:00:55.845 --> 00:00:58.023
Then you ask me a question
and if I can't answer it

00:00:58.023 --> 00:00:59.523
I'll pay you $500.

00:01:00.560 --> 00:01:02.464
So it's a 10 to one ratio.

00:01:02.464 --> 00:01:04.428
So the Indian figured
out he could probably ask

00:01:04.428 --> 00:01:07.520
at least one question that
Einstein couldn't answer

00:01:07.520 --> 00:01:08.868
so the game began.

00:01:08.868 --> 00:01:11.538
So he said to Albert
Einstein, you go first.

00:01:11.538 --> 00:01:15.705
So Einstein says to him, how
far is the moon from the Earth?

00:01:16.968 --> 00:01:18.499
And the Indian said, you know what

00:01:18.499 --> 00:01:20.720
we're a land of engineers and scientists,

00:01:20.720 --> 00:01:22.548
I should know the answer to that,

00:01:22.548 --> 00:01:26.508
but I can't give you the exact
answer, so here's $50 to you.

00:01:26.508 --> 00:01:29.072
So Einstein said, now it's your turn.

00:01:29.072 --> 00:01:30.664
So the Indian said to Einstein,

00:01:30.664 --> 00:01:32.420
what goes up the mountain with three legs,

00:01:32.420 --> 00:01:34.639
and comes down with four legs?

00:01:34.639 --> 00:01:36.800
And Einstein start to scratch his head,

00:01:36.800 --> 00:01:39.209
do all the algorithms
that he could think of,

00:01:39.209 --> 00:01:41.372
and finally he said, you know what,

00:01:41.372 --> 00:01:44.489
I don't know the answer,
here's $500 for you.

00:01:44.489 --> 00:01:45.980
So he looked at the Indian and said,

00:01:45.980 --> 00:01:49.292
before I ask you my next
question, what is the answer?

00:01:49.292 --> 00:01:51.272
What does go up the
mountain with three legs

00:01:51.272 --> 00:01:52.908
and come down with four legs?

00:01:52.908 --> 00:01:56.508
And the Indian went in his
pocket and he gave him $50.

00:01:56.508 --> 00:01:58.758
(laughing)

00:02:02.559 --> 00:02:05.224
And so Rick, whatever you do,

00:02:05.224 --> 00:02:07.825
don't get into a Q and A time in India,

00:02:07.825 --> 00:02:10.046
because you may come back with your wallet

00:02:10.046 --> 00:02:12.640
a little lighter than when you left.

00:02:12.640 --> 00:02:15.010
It's one of those countries where they can

00:02:15.010 --> 00:02:18.190
wear you out with
exhaustion with question,

00:02:18.190 --> 00:02:19.856
after question, after question.

00:02:19.856 --> 00:02:21.570
We're a questioning culture.

00:02:21.570 --> 00:02:25.198
Years ago I was flying
in from Thailand, Bangkok

00:02:25.198 --> 00:02:29.426
to New York, New Jersey, and
it's an exhausting flight.

00:02:29.426 --> 00:02:32.561
Those long long 14 hour stretches.

00:02:32.561 --> 00:02:34.327
You're just one out.

00:02:34.327 --> 00:02:37.615
So I got off the plane and
was heading to the gate

00:02:37.615 --> 00:02:40.385
where I was to catch my
connecting flight to Atlanta,

00:02:40.385 --> 00:02:43.205
and as I went to the
gate, I saw a lady sitting

00:02:43.205 --> 00:02:44.038
in the corner.

00:02:44.038 --> 00:02:46.395
I looked at the marque
and the marque showed

00:02:46.395 --> 00:02:49.607
a different city to what
I was heading to, Atlanta.

00:02:49.607 --> 00:02:52.335
So I said, "Mam, is this going to Atlanta,

00:02:52.335 --> 00:02:54.903
"or is this going to where
the marque says it is?"

00:02:54.903 --> 00:02:56.655
She said, "Oh it is going to Atlanta."

00:02:56.655 --> 00:02:58.040
I said, "That's good."

00:02:58.040 --> 00:02:59.751
So I went over to get a cup of coffee,

00:02:59.751 --> 00:03:01.924
and I heard the patter of feet behind me,

00:03:01.924 --> 00:03:03.563
and a tap on the shoulder.

00:03:03.563 --> 00:03:06.870
She said, "Excuse me,
are you Ravi Zacharias?"

00:03:06.870 --> 00:03:09.815
I said, "Yeah, I'm Ravi Zacharias."

00:03:09.815 --> 00:03:13.775
She said, "That is amazing,
absolutely amazing.

00:03:13.775 --> 00:03:17.183
"I didn't know you had questions as well."

00:03:17.183 --> 00:03:19.433
(laughing)

00:03:20.435 --> 00:03:24.724
You know I can't even
make up such a story.

00:03:24.724 --> 00:03:27.155
I thought to myself, do they really think

00:03:27.155 --> 00:03:28.956
you don't have questions?

00:03:28.956 --> 00:03:32.151
From the time you tottle
around you have question,

00:03:32.151 --> 00:03:34.343
after question, after question.

00:03:34.343 --> 00:03:37.162
I have four grandchildren,
the oldest is five.

00:03:37.162 --> 00:03:41.199
I am amazed at the questions
he actually does ask.

00:03:41.199 --> 00:03:43.383
One day we're sitting around the table

00:03:43.383 --> 00:03:45.667
and he was just staring
at me and then he says,

00:03:45.667 --> 00:03:49.167
"Papa, what is the meaning of sophomoric?"

00:03:51.535 --> 00:03:55.135
Boy's five, well he was
actually much younger than that,

00:03:55.135 --> 00:03:58.611
and I sounded sophomoric
trying to give him a definition

00:03:58.611 --> 00:04:01.116
of what sophomoric is all about,

00:04:01.116 --> 00:04:05.515
and they get deeper, and deeper,
and deeper into questions.

00:04:05.515 --> 00:04:08.932
The amazing thing in our time is not just

00:04:10.183 --> 00:04:13.979
that we ask questions,
but we have no answers

00:04:13.979 --> 00:04:17.669
for even the most basic questions of life.

00:04:17.669 --> 00:04:19.800
All of our definitions have gone.

00:04:19.800 --> 00:04:22.150
We no longer know how to define

00:04:22.150 --> 00:04:25.091
the most basic issues of life.

00:04:25.091 --> 00:04:27.295
I'll ask an average university student,

00:04:27.295 --> 00:04:29.795
what does it mean to be human?

00:04:31.587 --> 00:04:35.201
Chances are you will get a
dramatically different answer

00:04:35.201 --> 00:04:37.603
depending on which school you're at

00:04:37.603 --> 00:04:39.731
or which student is
answering the question.

00:04:39.731 --> 00:04:42.087
The story is told of these two Aussie's

00:04:42.087 --> 00:04:43.961
who had just gotten off a boat

00:04:43.961 --> 00:04:47.771
and had wanted to go out to
one of the pubs in London,

00:04:47.771 --> 00:04:50.007
and they went into that
pub, drank themselves with

00:04:50.007 --> 00:04:53.275
liquid refreshment into the
early hours of the morning,

00:04:53.275 --> 00:04:56.740
and as they came out into
the dense London fog,

00:04:56.740 --> 00:04:58.778
they're wobbling on their feet,

00:04:58.778 --> 00:05:00.987
and they see a man coming
in, unknown to them,

00:05:00.987 --> 00:05:04.047
he's a highly decorated
English naval officer,

00:05:04.047 --> 00:05:06.174
and so one of them looks at him and says,

00:05:06.174 --> 00:05:10.255
"Saya mate, can you tell us where we are?"

00:05:10.255 --> 00:05:12.343
And the officer, rather offended,

00:05:12.343 --> 00:05:15.670
pointed at his metals and said,
"Do you men know who I am?"

00:05:15.670 --> 00:05:17.815
At which point one
Aussie said to the other,

00:05:17.815 --> 00:05:19.627
"We are really in trouble now.

00:05:19.627 --> 00:05:23.203
"We don't know where we are
and he doesn't know who he is."

00:05:23.203 --> 00:05:25.453
(laughing)

00:05:28.571 --> 00:05:32.006
It's a fact, we really
don't know who we are.

00:05:32.006 --> 00:05:34.151
I just finished writing
a book, coauthored it

00:05:34.151 --> 00:05:36.307
with my colleague Vince Vitally.

00:05:36.307 --> 00:05:40.311
My chapters are dealing with
humanism, and relativism,

00:05:40.311 --> 00:05:43.667
and all these other isms that
Evee Hill would have said

00:05:43.667 --> 00:05:45.107
should be wasims.

00:05:45.107 --> 00:05:48.723
We're dealing with those
isms and I just went across

00:05:48.723 --> 00:05:53.087
the huge amount of literature
in humanistic philosophies,

00:05:53.087 --> 00:05:57.254
and I marveled at how the
very definitions have changed.

00:05:58.351 --> 00:06:00.991
You go back across time
from the Renaissance

00:06:00.991 --> 00:06:03.317
right now to the post modern definition

00:06:03.317 --> 00:06:05.119
of what it means to be human,

00:06:05.119 --> 00:06:08.447
and you will see how they've
gone down that vortex.

00:06:08.447 --> 00:06:11.839
They've been sucked into
the absence of definitions.

00:06:11.839 --> 00:06:16.167
In fact about the biggest insult
you pay an average humanist

00:06:16.167 --> 00:06:20.349
is to ask him or her to
really define what humanism

00:06:20.349 --> 00:06:21.811
is all about.

00:06:21.811 --> 00:06:26.447
We struggle with these
definitions for one simple reason.

00:06:26.447 --> 00:06:30.423
When we were in the
earliest days of the dawn

00:06:30.423 --> 00:06:34.771
of the created order, there
was only one restriction.

00:06:34.771 --> 00:06:37.171
Only one restriction.

00:06:37.171 --> 00:06:40.903
With all the possibilities,
one restriction.

00:06:40.903 --> 00:06:45.070
Not to eat of the tree of the
knowledge of good and evil.

00:06:45.947 --> 00:06:47.249
What does that mean?

00:06:47.249 --> 00:06:48.582
Do not play God.

00:06:51.287 --> 00:06:52.537
Don't play God.

00:06:53.911 --> 00:06:58.907
Don't be the self referencing
point of all absolutes

00:06:58.907 --> 00:07:03.499
and all definitions, and the
temptation was pretty to fold

00:07:03.499 --> 00:07:04.622
wasn't it?

00:07:04.622 --> 00:07:06.903
God said to them, in
the day that you choose

00:07:06.903 --> 00:07:10.078
to play this role, you will die.

00:07:10.078 --> 00:07:12.856
You will actually demean yourself.

00:07:12.856 --> 00:07:17.023
You will self destruct, but
the tempest said no, no, no.

00:07:18.188 --> 00:07:21.538
In the day you do this,
you will be as God,

00:07:21.538 --> 00:07:23.716
knowing good and evil.

00:07:23.716 --> 00:07:28.112
Meaning, you become the
definer of absolutes.

00:07:28.112 --> 00:07:32.520
Take a look at our world today
and see what has happened

00:07:32.520 --> 00:07:35.132
in the defining of absolutes.

00:07:35.132 --> 00:07:38.880
We are living in America,
possibly on the hinge

00:07:38.880 --> 00:07:41.534
on some of the darkest
days we've ever seen.

00:07:41.534 --> 00:07:45.524
Suddenly the most unpredictable
days we've ever seen.

00:07:45.524 --> 00:07:49.244
All over the world that I
go, I'm asked the question,

00:07:49.244 --> 00:07:51.812
what is happening in the United States?

00:07:51.812 --> 00:07:54.524
I was in Moscow, Russia in June,

00:07:54.524 --> 00:07:57.118
and a business man asked
me out for breakfast

00:07:57.118 --> 00:08:00.317
and at the end of the breakfast
he got up and said this.

00:08:00.317 --> 00:08:04.473
"I always had hope that
the future of the world

00:08:04.473 --> 00:08:07.097
"would hang on the wisdom and the ability

00:08:07.097 --> 00:08:08.862
"of the American people."

00:08:08.862 --> 00:08:11.070
He said, "That was my only hope."

00:08:11.070 --> 00:08:13.233
He said, "I no longer have that hope."

00:08:13.233 --> 00:08:14.657
And here's what he said.

00:08:14.657 --> 00:08:18.074
"They don't think rightly there anymore."

00:08:19.377 --> 00:08:20.905
This is a Russian man telling me.

00:08:20.905 --> 00:08:22.249
So what has happened?

00:08:22.249 --> 00:08:26.929
How do we in this pluralistic
culture do apologetics?

00:08:26.929 --> 00:08:29.158
What is apologetics?

00:08:29.158 --> 00:08:32.417
Apologetics is that
discipline which comes from

00:08:32.417 --> 00:08:34.609
the Greek word apologia.

00:08:34.609 --> 00:08:37.421
Which literally means to give an answer.

00:08:37.421 --> 00:08:40.465
To give an answer to
the questions of people,

00:08:40.465 --> 00:08:43.421
but it has that twin responsibility

00:08:43.421 --> 00:08:47.705
of making truth claims
clear and giving answers

00:08:47.705 --> 00:08:50.081
to the questions that people ask.

00:08:50.081 --> 00:08:52.061
The apostle Peter says,

00:08:52.061 --> 00:08:56.037
"But to set apart Christ
in your heart as lord,

00:08:56.037 --> 00:08:58.825
"and always be prepared to give an answer

00:08:58.825 --> 00:09:02.697
"to anyone who asks of you
the reason for the hope

00:09:02.697 --> 00:09:04.989
"that is within you, and to do that

00:09:04.989 --> 00:09:06.969
"with gentleness and respect."

00:09:06.969 --> 00:09:10.016
I cannot think of a more
beautiful definition

00:09:10.016 --> 00:09:14.198
of what apologetics is, and
this came from a fisherman

00:09:14.198 --> 00:09:18.302
who had also seen that
extraordinary disclosure

00:09:18.302 --> 00:09:21.122
in the transfiguration of the lord Jesus.

00:09:21.122 --> 00:09:25.289
Such a spectacular event,
vouchsafed to only a hand few.

00:09:26.370 --> 00:09:29.746
So spectacular was it
that he said to his lord,

00:09:29.746 --> 00:09:31.441
Let's stay right here.

00:09:31.441 --> 00:09:33.616
I don't wanna go down there again.

00:09:33.616 --> 00:09:37.158
But the lord told him that
they had work to be done,

00:09:37.158 --> 00:09:41.155
and took them back into
the mainstream of people.

00:09:41.155 --> 00:09:45.474
You and I would love to be
in that cloistered existence

00:09:45.474 --> 00:09:47.980
of a spectacular revelation,

00:09:47.980 --> 00:09:50.740
but this is our time in history.

00:09:50.740 --> 00:09:54.845
Regardless how bleak it may
seem, how dark it may seem.

00:09:54.845 --> 00:09:58.104
My colleague and I were talking
about this earlier today,

00:09:58.104 --> 00:09:59.648
and I made the comment to him.

00:09:59.648 --> 00:10:02.740
I said, "You know, this
is the most open time

00:10:02.740 --> 00:10:05.393
"that I have ever sensed, but it is also

00:10:05.393 --> 00:10:09.144
"the most difficult time
at which to give clear

00:10:09.144 --> 00:10:11.380
"and convincing answers."

00:10:11.380 --> 00:10:16.257
The struggles we have began
about 40 to 50 years ago,

00:10:16.257 --> 00:10:19.033
and a Canadian writer said this.

00:10:19.033 --> 00:10:22.420
"In the 1950s, kids lost their innocence.

00:10:22.420 --> 00:10:24.460
"They were liberated from their parents

00:10:24.460 --> 00:10:27.684
"be whelping jobs, cars,
and lyrics, and music

00:10:27.684 --> 00:10:31.060
"that gave rise to a new
term. the generation gap.

00:10:31.060 --> 00:10:34.376
"In the 1960s, kids lost their authority.

00:10:34.376 --> 00:10:37.720
"it was the decade of
protest, church, state,

00:10:37.720 --> 00:10:40.196
"and parents were all called into question

00:10:40.196 --> 00:10:41.453
"and found wanting.

00:10:41.453 --> 00:10:45.220
"their authority was rejected,
yet nothing ever replaced it.

00:10:45.220 --> 00:10:48.160
"In the 1970s, kids lost their love.

00:10:48.160 --> 00:10:52.434
"it was the decade of Mesum,
dominated by hyphenated words

00:10:52.434 --> 00:10:53.844
"beginning with self.

00:10:53.844 --> 00:10:56.768
"Self-image, self-esteem, self-assertion.

00:10:56.768 --> 00:10:59.184
"It made for a very lonely world.

00:10:59.184 --> 00:11:02.045
"Kids learned everything
there was to know about sex.

00:11:02.045 --> 00:11:04.884
"Forgot everything there
was to know about true love,

00:11:04.884 --> 00:11:06.744
"and few had the verve to tell them

00:11:06.744 --> 00:11:09.024
"that there was indeed a difference.

00:11:09.024 --> 00:11:11.500
"In the 1980s kids lost their hope.

00:11:11.500 --> 00:11:14.287
"Stripped of innocence,
authority, and love,

00:11:14.287 --> 00:11:17.124
"and plagued by the horror
of a nuclear nightmare.

00:11:17.124 --> 00:11:20.184
"Large and growing
numbers of this generation

00:11:20.184 --> 00:11:22.764
"have stopped believing in the future."

00:11:22.764 --> 00:11:24.608
I put this as a post script.

00:11:24.608 --> 00:11:28.676
In the 1990s, kids have
lost their power to reason.

00:11:28.676 --> 00:11:31.556
Lost in a world of cyberspace,

00:11:31.556 --> 00:11:34.224
they have now personalized objects

00:11:34.224 --> 00:11:37.375
and totally subjectivized reality,

00:11:37.375 --> 00:11:40.958
and they are now
imprisoned in a deep world

00:11:42.744 --> 00:11:44.744
of their own loneliness.

00:11:45.744 --> 00:11:49.911
Having personalized objects,
and subjectivized reality,

00:11:50.860 --> 00:11:53.588
they look deep inside of them.

00:11:53.588 --> 00:11:55.921
They really have no answers.

00:11:57.068 --> 00:12:01.235
They only sense that sense
of isolation or alienation.

00:12:02.844 --> 00:12:05.244
Earlier in the year I had
the privilege of speaking

00:12:05.244 --> 00:12:06.880
at the passion conference.

00:12:06.880 --> 00:12:11.047
About 40,000 young people
listening live to that session,

00:12:12.008 --> 00:12:16.268
and after just a number
of powerful speakers

00:12:16.268 --> 00:12:19.196
the two most important issues for which

00:12:19.196 --> 00:12:21.324
they came forward for counseling.

00:12:21.324 --> 00:12:23.036
These are university students.

00:12:23.036 --> 00:12:25.507
If nobody had told you, you'd never guess.

00:12:25.507 --> 00:12:27.896
Number one problem plaguing the young

00:12:27.896 --> 00:12:32.576
that came forward for
counseling was on pornography.

00:12:32.576 --> 00:12:35.168
Number two was in suicide.

00:12:35.168 --> 00:12:37.774
The first demeaned the other.

00:12:37.774 --> 00:12:41.336
They ultimately demeaned themselves,

00:12:41.336 --> 00:12:45.008
and as I hear their voices
and hear their struggle,

00:12:45.008 --> 00:12:48.624
we are living in a world
of billions of people

00:12:48.624 --> 00:12:52.660
with each on in their
solitary world of struggle

00:12:52.660 --> 00:12:53.904
and questions.

00:12:53.904 --> 00:12:56.980
You and I believe, if you're
a follower of Jesus Christ,

00:12:56.980 --> 00:13:00.400
that in Jesus alone we have the answers

00:13:00.400 --> 00:13:04.976
that are correspondingly
true to every question raised

00:13:04.976 --> 00:13:08.498
and coherent when all of the
answers are given together.

00:13:08.498 --> 00:13:10.556
Correspondence and coherence.

00:13:10.556 --> 00:13:14.108
The two tests for truth,
and in the person of Christ

00:13:14.108 --> 00:13:18.039
we find those answers to
the four deepest questions

00:13:18.039 --> 00:13:19.962
that bridge the head to the heart.

00:13:19.962 --> 00:13:21.536
What are those questions?

00:13:21.536 --> 00:13:23.665
The question of origin,
the question of meaning,

00:13:23.665 --> 00:13:26.096
the question of morality,
and the question of destiny.

00:13:26.096 --> 00:13:28.164
That forms your world view.

00:13:28.164 --> 00:13:31.360
Origin, meaning, morality, and destiny,

